The tumulus was constructed by leveling a large area of approximately 40 meters in diameter and building the mound using rammed-earth techniques. The tomb has an octagonal type with a diagonal length of approximately 30 meters. The burial facility is a {{ill|horizontal stone chamber with frontal entrance|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft}} opening to the south. The chamber is constructed using tuff-cut stones, with a rectangular floor plan and a trapezoidal cross-section. The interior likely contained a lacquered wooden coffin. burial goods such as human bones (teeth), iron nails, and {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were discovered during the excavation.

The tomb is dated to the late {{ill|7th century|ja|7世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, making it a representative example of the end of the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Based on its location, map_size, and construction, it is thought to be the burial site of {{ill|Prince Kusakabe|ja|草壁皇子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Crown Prince to Emperor Tenmu.

== burial ==
The burial chamber features a unique horizontal stone structure:
* '''area:''' Length 3.06m; width 2.12m; estimated height 2.50m.
* '''Material:''' Rectangular tuff blocks measuring 50cm × 50cm × 30cm.
* '''built:''' The walls were built vertically up to a height of 1.27m, after which they were inclined inward at approximately 60 degrees, creating a trapezoidal cross-section.
* '''Interior:''' The floor was paved with two layers of stone, and a section of the floor was coated with plaster. 

burial goods recovered include more than 50 iron nails, lacquer fragments, and coffin fittings, suggesting the use of a lacquered wooden coffin. The presence of large nails implies that the coffin rested on a wooden plattype.

== Historical Context ==
The tomb is believed to be the burial site of {{ill|Prince Kusakabe|ja|草壁皇子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who served as Crown Prince to Emperor Tenmu. Prince Kusakabe died prematurely in 689 AD, leaving a significant legacy through his descendants, including Emperor Monmu and Empress Genshō.

While the site is not officially Historic Site1 as a historic landmark, its map_size, construction, and historical significance make it an important archaeological site. The burial chamber has been reconstructed and is on display at the {{ill|Nara Prefectural Kashihara Archaeological Institute|ja|奈良県立橿原考古学研究所|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Museum.

== Related Facilities ==
* {{ill|Nara Prefectural Kashihara Archaeological Institute|ja|奈良県立橿原考古学研究所|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Museum (Kashihara, Nara Prefecture): Reconstructed burial chamber from Tsukamyojin Kofun is on display.

